        <body>
            <p>To the Editor of the Asmonean</p>
            <p>Dear Sir</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I have been requested by <persName>Mr. L. Newman</persName><lb/> to
                solicit your attention to a new edition of his<lb/> Hebrew Grammar which he is about
                to publish in<lb/> this country. <persName>Mr. Newman's</persName> grammar has
                passed<lb/> through several editions and is favorably known<lb/> in
                    <placeName>England</placeName>, where I myself have used it in the<lb/> Hebrew
                National School <placeName>Birmingham</placeName>, and where<lb/> it is generally
                considered as best adapted for Hebrew<lb/> schools. <persName>Mr.
                    <sic>Newmans</sic></persName> long experience as a teacher<lb/> has taught him
                practically what a Hebrew Grammar<lb/> ought to be, and has enabled him to produce
                one<lb/> well digested in its system clear in rules, brief<lb/>
                <del>in</del> but distinct in its directions and condensing<lb/> every thing that
                the student needs, within a<lb/> moderate number of pages. It thus combines<lb/>
                    sperspicacity<add>?</add> and completeness with brevity<lb/> and good
                arrangement.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I think the Jewish Chronicle <placeName>London</placeName>
                <date>Nov.7 54.</date><lb/> speaks in high terms of this Grammar, the<lb/>
                publication of which in this country most teachers<lb/> will hail with
                satisfaction</p>
            <p rend="indent(10)">Yours very Respectfully</p>
            <p rend="indent(11)">
                <persName role="author">MrsRaphall<add>?</add></persName>
            </p>
            <p>
                <placeName>94 MacDougal St</placeName>
            </p>
            <p><date>6<hi rend="sup">th</hi>. Nov./55</date>.</p>
        </body>
